					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">1. The read buffer will be filled with <strong>semi-random</strong> data, and it will mess up the VRAM address. See below.
<br />
<br />2. Semi-random data will be written. The actual address is tricky, though. See below.
<br />
<br />3. $2003 does two things - it specifies where the next $2004 (and $4014) write will go, and it has some sort of effect on the first two sprites.
<br />
<br />4. This is correct, though the exact details are not fully understood. Now that I have a CopyNES, though, I should be able to do some more testing on it.
<br />
<br />5. No, since the SPR-RAM address ($2003) is not connected while rendering. You <strong>can</strong> read $2004 during rendering, though, and it will reveal the PPU's internal SPR-RAM accesses (incidentally, this is how I figured out the messed-up sprite overflow flag behavior).
<br />
<br />6. Correct. If you write during VBLANK or when rendering is off, the value $00 will be written instead. An easy way around this is to switch to mode 2 and then do your writing.
<br />
<br />7. Not sure what you're asking.
<br />
<br />8. Yes.
<br />
<br />9. I don't know exactly how PPU cycle offsets figure into synchronization issues.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Quietust, QMT Productions
<br />P.S. If you don't get this note, let me know and I'll write you another.</div>
