			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">As far as I understand it, the NMI and IRQ lines are latched during the last clock of an instruction, meaning that the value present just before the last block begins is what is used. This means that an instruction which causes them to be asserted during its last cycle won't result in an interrupt until after the next instruction executes. No delays, just the detail of when the value is sampled. I'm not an expert in digital electronics, but I think this is all due to designing things using clocked logic, which results in general structures resembling a pipeline. When things get clocked they use the value that was present just before the clock, so each stage adds one clock of latency from input to output.</div>

